# Copy to `.env.local` for local development (never commit `.env.local`).
#
# ── Local dev (recommended) ────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Canonical web origin used for metadataBase, sitemap, and canonical links.
NEXT_PUBLIC_SITE_URL=http://localhost:5280

# Leave API origin empty: Next.js proxies `/api/*` and `/uploads/*` to the
# backend (see `next.config.ts` → localhost:5050). Run the backend separately.
# When testing from a phone via LAN (http://192.168.x.x:5280), do NOT set this to
# http://localhost:5050 — the phone's browser resolves localhost to itself. Empty
# origin uses same-origin `/api` + rewrites. Or use your PC's LAN IP for the API.
# `next.config.ts` keeps `/api` → backend rewrites when this is empty **or** points at
# localhost (so LAN phones still get a proxy). Only a non-loopback URL disables rewrites.
NEXT_PUBLIC_API_ORIGIN=

# Optional server-only API origin for Next server runtime (metadata/sitemap).
# Useful when server-side fetches cannot use browser rewrites directly.
# INTERNAL_API_URL=http://127.0.0.1:5050

# Google OAuth — Web client ID (readers /profile sign-in). Local: set here.
# Production: set the SAME key in Vercel → web-next → Environment Variables, then Redeploy.
NEXT_PUBLIC_GOOGLE_CLIENT_ID=

# ── Production / split deployment ───────────────────────────────────────────
# Set to your public API base URL (no trailing slash), e.g. https://api.example.com
# Must match an origin listed in the backend `CLIENT_URL` or `CLIENT_URLS` for CORS.
# NEXT_PUBLIC_API_ORIGIN=https://api.example.com
